’ Protecting Places -- tDemons of Fate in Macedonian Folk Beliefs -- tGog and Magog in the Slovenian Folk Tradition -- tSystematization of the Concept of Demonic and Evil in Mongolian Folk Religion -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe authors—recognized historians, ethnologists, folklorists coming from four continents—present the latest research findings on the relationship, coexistence and conflicts of popular belief systems, Judeo-Christian mythology and demonology in medieval and modern Europe. The present volume focuses on the divergence between Western and Eastern evolution, on the different relationship of learned demonology to popular belief systems in the two parts of Europe. It discusses the conflict of saints, healers, seers, shamans with the representatives of evil; the special function of escorting, protecting, possessing, harming and healing spirits; the role of the dead, the ghosts, of pre-Christian, Jewish and Christian spirit-world, the antagonism of the devil and the saint.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aDemonology. 0aWitchcraft. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnthropology, Balkan, Early modern Europe, Folklore, Jews, Medieval, Persecutions.1 aBirtalan, Ágnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaniczay, Gábor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaniczay, Gábor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKropej, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuznetsova, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiliequist, Jonas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLáng, Benedek, econtributor.4ctb4ht